# clean memory
rm(list = ls())

link='https://github.com/EvansDataScience/data/raw/master/eduwa.rda'

Data from Counting

Counting expresses numerical values. They could be represented with bar plots if their frequency table had few discrete values, but that is not generally the case. For example, the variable Reduced.Lunch informs how many kids there are in each school that have that lunch for a reduced price. We have more than 2000 schools, so it is unlikely we find few different values. This is how many different values we have:

# how many unique values
length(unique(eduwa$Reduced.Lunch))
## [1] 172

There are too many different values. Then, the bar plot is not a good idea (and neither a frequency table), as the bar plot produces a bar for each unique value in the data, counting how many times this value appeared. This is how a bar plot looks for this variable:

lunchDF=as.data.frame(table(eduwa$Reduced.Lunch))
names(lunchDF)=c("Beneficiaries","Count")

library(ggplot2)
base1=ggplot(data=lunchDF, aes(x=Beneficiaries,Count))
bar1=base1+geom_bar(stat = "identity")
bar1

Numerical data requires statistical exploration with some questions in mind:

  • What is the representative value? Generally the mean, or median.

  • How good is the representative value? You need some measure of dispersion. For the mean you have the standard deviation and coefficient of variation, and for the median the median absolute deviation.

  • Does the shape of the distribution differs from a normal distribution? If there is asymmetry, is it big enough to show outliers? You need some measure of symmetry and shape (a.k.a. kurtosis).

First, let’s take a look at the basic statistical information:

summary(eduwa$Reduced.Lunch)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
##    0.00    5.00   25.50   33.53   47.00  301.00     131

This information may give us a general idea on how the data on Reduced lunch is behaving, so we select the plot that highlights that behavior. Let me try a box plot:

  1. Keep all the summary values but the count on NAs.
(statVals=summary(eduwa$Reduced.Lunch,digits = 3)[1:6])
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##     0.0     5.0    25.5    33.5    47.0   301.0

Let me put some of those values in the boxplot y-axis:

library(magrittr)
statVals=statVals%>%as.vector() 

base= ggplot(eduwa,aes(y = Reduced.Lunch))  
b1= base + geom_boxplot() 
b1=b1 +coord_flip()
b1=b1+ scale_y_continuous(breaks = statVals)
b1

This boxplot shows outliers, that means there is an upper threshold. I can get that value using the interquartile range, which is:

# difference between q3 and q1:
(theIQR=IQR(eduwa$Reduced.Lunch,na.rm = T))
## [1] 42

Then, you simply add (substract) to the top (bottom) quartile the IQR multiply by a factor (typically 1.5) to get the upper (lower) threshold:

# just the upper threshold
(upperT=summary(eduwa$Reduced.Lunch)[[5]] + theIQR*1.5)
## [1] 110

Knowing the upper threshold, I can compute the amount of upper outliers:

(numOut=sum(eduwa$Reduced.Lunch>upperT,na.rm = T))
## [1] 96

I can annotate my boxplot with this value:

annUpper=paste0('Threshold:',upperT)
annOutN=paste0('#Outlying schools: ',numOut)
b1ann = b1 + geom_hline(yintercept = upperT,
                     color='grey8',
                     linetype="dotted",
                     size=2) 
b1ann=b1ann + annotate(geom = 'text',
              label=annUpper,
              y = upperT+5,
              x=0.2,
              angle=90)

b1ann=b1ann + annotate(geom = 'text',
              label=annOutN,
              y = upperT+60,
              x=0.1,
              angle=0)
b1ann

You can not see clearly the horizontal values, and the vertical values are confusing, then:

b1x=b1ann+ theme(axis.text.y = element_blank(),
          axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),
          axis.title.y = element_blank())
b1x + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 60,size = 7,vjust = 0.5))

In general, numerical data are prone to have outliers in real life. It is not common to speak about outliers in ordinal data since they have few levels. The less objective side of finding outliers lies in the decision of what “normal” means. In the case of the boxplot, the decision has been to accept as normal the values that have a prudent distance from the first or last quartile. The distance chosen was 1.5 times the IQR. Then, if a outlier is found, the whisker ends in a position different than the actual minimum or maximal value of the data.

The summary command can be supplemented with some measures of spread or dispersion:

# standard deviation:
sd(eduwa$Reduced.Lunch,na.rm = T)
## [1] 36.55684
# median absolute deviation:
mad(eduwa$Reduced.Lunch,na.rm = T)
## [1] 30.3933
# coefficient of variation
library(DescTools)
CoefVar(eduwa$Reduced.Lunch,
        na.rm = T,
        unbiased=T,
        conf.level = 0.95)
##      est   low.ci   upr.ci 
## 1.090575 1.035625 1.151947

There is also some measures of shape:

# asymmetry
Skew(eduwa$Reduced.Lunch,
     na.rm = T,
     conf.level = 0.95,
     ci.type = "bca",
     R=2500)
##     skew   lwr.ci   upr.ci 
## 2.158124 1.893129 2.472733
# kurtosis
Kurt(eduwa$Reduced.Lunch,
     na.rm = T,conf.level = 0.95,
     ci.type = "bca",R=2500)
##     kurt   lwr.ci   upr.ci 
## 7.311024 5.254457 9.909286
# confidence interval for the mean
MeanCI(eduwa$Reduced.Lunch,
     na.rm = T)
##     mean   lwr.ci   upr.ci 
## 33.53441 32.03831 35.03051

What do we know right now?

  1. The data is skewed, with a right tail.
  2. The data is concentrated in a small group of values.
  3. In this situation, the median is more informative than the mean.

Let me save that information for future annotations:

cv=CoefVar(eduwa$Reduced.Lunch,na.rm = T)
sd=SD(eduwa$Reduced.Lunch,na.rm = T)
md=Median(eduwa$Reduced.Lunch,na.rm = T)
mn=Mean(eduwa$Reduced.Lunch,na.rm = T)
mn.low=MeanCI(eduwa$Reduced.Lunch,
     na.rm = T)[['lwr.ci']]
mn.up=MeanCI(eduwa$Reduced.Lunch,
     na.rm = T)[['upr.ci']]
sk=Skew(eduwa$Reduced.Lunch,
     na.rm = T)

A key visual for numerical data is the histogram. The histogram looks like a bar plot. In both cases the height of the bars represent counts, but the bars in the histogram are consecutive while the bases of the bars are numeric intervals (binwidth informs the length of the intervals). Histograms help you discover peaks in the distributions. Let’s make one:

#ggplot
WIDTH=10
library(ggplot2)
base= ggplot(eduwa)  
h1= base + geom_histogram(aes(x = Reduced.Lunch),
                          binwidth = WIDTH) 
h1

let’s do some annotations:

# texts
annMean=paste0('Mean:',round(mn))
annSk=paste0('Skeness:',round(sk,2))

# adding
h1+ geom_vline(xintercept = mn,color='red') + # mean as line
    annotate(geom = 'text',
             label=annMean,
              y = 400,
              x=mn+5,
              angle=90) + # mean as value
    annotate(geom = 'text', color='blue',
             label=annSk,
              y = 100,
              x=upperT+100,
              angle=0) # skewness

What else would you do?

Measurement

A simplistic idea of measurement tells you the times a particular unit is present in the unit of analysis; which allows for the presence of decimal places. There are variables that could even have negative values.

Let’s analyze the variable Student.Teacher.Ratio:

summary(eduwa$Student.Teacher.Ratio)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
##    0.10   16.20   18.30   18.95   20.20  330.00     329

Notice that the maximum value is very far from the mean and the median, this announces the presence of outliers, which can be revealed with a boxplot:

base=ggplot(eduwa) + theme_classic()
box2=base + geom_boxplot(aes(y=Student.Teacher.Ratio))
box2=box2 + coord_flip()
box2

Now, let’s see if this is a multimodal distribution (more tna one peak). Let’s take a look at the histogram:

hist2=base + geom_histogram(aes(x=Student.Teacher.Ratio))
hist2

You can recover the count of each bar in the histogram using ggplot_built:

ggplot_build(hist2)$data[[1]]%>%head()

We know this variable has one peak, is highly skewed, and has outliers at the top and the bottom values. We could try to combine all that in one visual:

library(ggpubr)
ggarrange(hist2,box2,align='v',ncol = 1,heights = 2:1)

As you see, that is not an exact match. An alternative can be the violin plot.

base=ggplot(eduwa, aes(x=0,y=Student.Teacher.Ratio))+
            theme_classic()

vio=base+geom_violin(trim=FALSE, fill="gray90")

viobox=vio+geom_boxplot(width=0.2)
viobox=viobox + coord_flip()
viobox

We could inform the amount of outliers:

theVar=eduwa$Student.Teacher.Ratio
theIQR=IQR(theVar,na.rm = T)
upperT=summary(theVar)[[5]] + theIQR*1.5
lowerT=summary(theVar)[[2]] - theIQR*1.5

# top
(numOutUp=sum(eduwa$Student.Teacher.Ratio>upperT,na.rm = T))
## [1] 102
# bottom
(numOutLw=sum(eduwa$Student.Teacher.Ratio<lowerT,na.rm = T))
## [1] 83

We know there are 185 outliers (83 at the bottom values and 102 at the top). Let’s annotate the plot with that information:

# prepare texts:
annOutUN=paste0(numOutUp,' schools\nabove ',upperT)
annOutLN=paste0(numOutLw,' schools\nbelow ',lowerT)

# plotting
viobox=viobox  + labs(x='')
viobox + annotate(geom = 'text',
              label=annOutUN,
              y = upperT+60,
              x=0.1,
              angle=0) + 
         annotate(geom = 'text',
              label=annOutLN,
              y = lowerT,
              x=0.5,
              angle=0) + 
        theme(axis.text.y = element_blank(), # no text on y
              axis.ticks.y = element_blank(),# no ticks on y
              axis.line.y = element_blank()) # no line on y

The violin plot will inform the presence of peaks, but not on the maximum value of the peak as the histogram shows.
